{"title_page": "Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Short description|United Kingdom law}}\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851\n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\n|long_title           = <sup>An Act to amend an Act of Parliament of Ireland of the Twenty-fifth Year of King George the Third, for explaining and amending several Laws for the Encouragement of Agriculture, so far as relates to Leases for the Erection of Mills</sup>\n|statute_book_chapter = 14 Vict. c.7\n|introduced_by        = \n|territorial_extent   = [[Ireland]]\n|royal_assent         = 11 April 1851\n|commencement         = \n|repeal_date          = 21st July 2009<ref>{{cite web |title=LAND AND CONVEYANCING LAW REFORM ACT 2009 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/print#sec1 |website=[[Irish Statute Book]] |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n|amendments           =\n|related_legislation  = \n|repealing_legislation= [[Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009]]\n|status               = Repealed\n|original_text        = \n|use_new_UK-LEG       = \n|legislation_history  =\n}}\nThe '''Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851''' is an act of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The act extended the powers of various members of the clergy and landowners to authorise and lease their land to build [[watermill]]s to [[Ireland]], which was previously omitted. The act received Royal Assent on 11 April 1851.<ref name=\"s7\">{{cite book |title=A Collection of the Public General Statutes passed in the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Years of the reign of Her Majesty Queen Victoria: Being the Fouth Session of the Fifteenth Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1864 |publisher=George Edward Eyre and William Spottiswoode |page=83}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\nThe provisions of the act include:\n*Extending the powers conferred in the [[Exportation Act 1785]] to Ireland.<ref name=\"s7\" />\n**Powers were given to bishops and members of the clergy, governors and fellows of hospitals or colleges, and anyone \"in possession in Law or Equity of an Estate in [[Fee Tail]] or ... [[Trust law|in trust]]\" to lease their land to others for the building of mills or associated infrastructure.<ref name=\"s7\" />\n\n==Repeal==\nAll parts of the Act still in effect were repealed by the [[Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009]] of the [[Oireachtas|Irish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/schedule/2/enacted/en/html |website=[[Irish Statute Book]] |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Law|United Kingdom|Ireland}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UK legislation|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851}}\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 1851]]\n[[Category:1851 in British law]]\n[[Category:Irish law]]\n\n\n{{UK-law-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Short description|United Kingdom law}}\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851\n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\n|long_title           = <sup>An Act to amend an Act of Parliament of Ireland of the Twenty-fifth Year of King George the Third, for explaining and amending several Laws for the Encouragement of Agriculture, so far as relates to Leases for the Erection of Mills</sup>\n|statute_book_chapter = 14 Vict. c.7\n|introduced_by        = \n|territorial_extent   = [[Ireland]]\n|royal_assent         = 11 April 1851\n|commencement         = \n|repeal_date          = 21st July 2009<ref>{{cite web |title=LAND AND CONVEYANCING LAW REFORM ACT 2009 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/print#sec1 |website=[[Irish Statute Book]] |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n|amendments           =\n|related_legislation  = \n|repealing_legislation= [[Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009]]\n|status               = Repealed\n|original_text        = \n|use_new_UK-LEG       = \n|legislation_history  =\n}}\nThe '''Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851''' is an act of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The act extended the powers of various members of the clergy and landowners to authorise and lease their land to build [[watermill]]s to [[Ireland]], which was previously omitted. The act received Royal Assent on 11 April 1851.<ref name=\"s7\">{{cite book |title=A Collection of the Public General Statutes passed in the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Years of the reign of Her Majesty Queen Victoria: Being the Fouth Session of the Fifteenth Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1864 |publisher=George Edward Eyre and William Spottiswoode |page=83}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\nThe provisions of the act include:\n*Extending the powers conferred in the [[Exportation Act 1785]] to Ireland.<ref name=\"s7\" />\n**Powers were given to bishops and members of the clergy, governors and fellows of hospitals or colleges, and anyone \"in possession in Law or Equity of an Estate in [[Fee Tail]] or ... [[Trust law|in trust]]\" to lease their land to others for the building of mills or associated infrastructure.<ref name=\"s7\" />\n\n==Repeal==\nAll parts of the Act still in effect were repealed by the [[Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009]] of the [[Irish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/schedule/2/enacted/en/html |website=[[Irish Statute Book]] |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Law|United Kingdom|Ireland}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UK legislation|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leases for Mills (Ireland) Act 1851}}\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 1851]]\n[[Category:1851 in British law]]\n[[Category:Irish law]]\n\n\n{{UK-law-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toIrish parliament(link changed toOireachtas) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leases_for_Mills_(Ireland)_Act_1851"}
{"title_page": "Amarashilpi Jakanachari", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n[[File:Kaidala Temple.jpg|thumbnail|Chennakeshava temple, Kaidala]]\n\n'''Amarashilpi Jakana chary''' was an Indian legendary sculptor credited with building many fine temples for the [[Kalyani Chalukya]]s and [[Hoysala]]s.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n== His life ==\n[[File:Entrance of ChannaKeshawa Temple - Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n[[File:Interiors of Chennakeshava Temple - Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Interior of Chennakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\nJakanna chary was born in a small village called Kaidala, 9&nbsp;km from [[Tumkur]], [[Karnataka]]. The original name of the town as per records was [[Kridapura]]. His life was one of love and dedication to art. His career began when [[Nripa Haya]] ruled as a local chieftain of the area. {{citation needed|date=November 2012}}  He left home shortly after his marriage seeking fame in his field of work. He travelled far and wide building many temples and became so engrossed in his work that he forgot all about his wife. \n[[File:Krishna Idol Carved on the Entrnace of Channakeshava Temple-kaidala.JPG|thumb|Krishna in relief at the entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\n== Jakanna chary and his son ==\n\nJakana chary's wife gave birth to his child, named [[Dankanacharya]]. Dankanacharya himself grew up to become a famous sculptor and set out to find his father. At Belur, he found a job as a sculptor and noticed a flaw in a figure sculpted by the great Jakanacharya himself. Dankanacharya told Jakanacharya that the stone which he was carving had a toad living inside which was a considered to be a flaw by the sculptors. Furious at this, Jakana chary challenged to cut off his right hand if the young sculptor was correct in his assessment of the sculpture. Dankanacharya chiselled the place where the flaw was present and a toad jumped out with a little water flowing from that spot. Upon testing the figure, the flaw was indeed revealed and Jakana chary kept his promise and cut off his right hand.<ref name=sharath>{{cite news|last1=Sharath|first1=Lakshmi|title=A Craftman's tale|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/a-craftsmans-tale/article651259.ece|accessdate=18 August 2015|newspaper=The Hindu, Newspaper|date=16 March 2009}}</ref> Eventually, the two sculptors become aware of their relationship as father and son.\n[[File:Vishnu Idol adorning Entrance of ChennaKeshawa Temple Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Vishnu relief adorning entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\n== Chennakeshava temple ==\n\nSubsequently, Jakanacharya received a vision to build the [[Chennakeshava temple]] in his native place Kridapura. After this was completed, legend has it that God restored his right hand. In celebration of this incident, Kridapura was henceforth called ''Kaidala''. The term ''Kai'' in [[Kannada]] means \"hand\".<ref name=sharath/> Local non-government organizations in the state of Karnataka have been trying to raise funds to protect the Chennakeshava temple at Kaidala.\n\n== The Jakanna chary Awards ==\n\nThe government of Karnataka confers the  ''[[Jakanachari Award]]s'' to talented sculptors and craftsmen from the state every year to celebrate the contributions of this legendary architect. {{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Film ==\n\nIn 1964, a Kannada biographical film about him, ''Amarashilpi Jakanachari'' starring [[Kalyan Kumar]] was produced. The veteran cinematographer BS Ranga was instrumental in the making of this movie, the first Kannada colour movie.<ref name=deccan>{{cite news|last=DHNS|title=He brought colour to Kannada cinema|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/120234/he-brought-colour-kannada-cinema.html|accessdate=21 June 2012|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=12 December 2010}}</ref> Also in 1964, a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] remake of the movie titled [[Amara Shilpi Jakkanna]] starring [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] and [[Saroja Devi]] was released to popular success.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/aug92005/spectrum92548200588.asp Article on the life of Jakanachari]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2000/01/01/stories/04012108.htm Article on Jakanachari state award]\n*[https://archive.is/20130121103109/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Aug232007/state2007082320946.asp?section=updatenews Article on Jakanachari state award]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amarashilpi Jakanachari}}\n[[Category:History of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Tumkur]]\n[[Category:Kannada people]]\n[[Category:Indian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Artists from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:12th-century Indian sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n[[File:Kaidala Temple.jpg|thumbnail|Chennakeshava temple, Kaidala]]\n\n'''Amarashilpi Jakana chary''' was an Indian legendary sculptor credited with building many fine temples for the [[Kalyani Chalukya]]s and [[Hoysala]]s.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n== His life ==\n[[File:Entrance of ChannaKeshawa Temple - Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n[[File:Interiors of Chennakeshava Temple - Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Interior of Chennakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\nJakanna chary was born in a small village called Kaidala, 9&nbsp;km from [[Tumkur]], [[Karnataka]]. The original name of the town as per records was [[Kridapura]]. His life was one of love and dedication to art. His career began when [[Nripa Haya]] ruled as a local chieftain of the area. {{citation needed|date=November 2012}}  He left home shortly after his marriage seeking fame in his field of work. He travelled far and wide building many temples and became so engrossed in his work that he forgot all about his wife. \n[[File:Krishna Idol Carved on the Entrnace of Channakeshava Temple-kaidala.JPG|thumb|Krishna in relief at the entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\n== Jakanna chary and his son ==\n\nJakanachari's wife gave birth to his child, named [[Dankanacharya]]. Dankanacharya himself grew up to become a famous sculptor and set out to find his father. At Belur, he found a job as a sculptor and noticed a flaw in a figure sculpted by the great Jakanacharya himself. Dankanacharya told Jakanacharya that the stone which he was carving had a toad living inside which was a considered to be a flaw by the sculptors. Furious at this, Jakanacharya challenged to cut off his right hand if the young sculptor was correct in his assessment of the sculpture. Dankanacharya chiselled the place where the flaw was present and a toad jumped out with a little water flowing from that spot. Upon testing the figure, the flaw was indeed revealed and Jakanacharya kept his promise and cut off his right hand.<ref name=sharath>{{cite news|last1=Sharath|first1=Lakshmi|title=A Craftman's tale|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/a-craftsmans-tale/article651259.ece|accessdate=18 August 2015|newspaper=The Hindu, Newspaper|date=16 March 2009}}</ref> Eventually, the two sculptors become aware of their relationship as father and son.\n[[File:Vishnu Idol adorning Entrance of ChennaKeshawa Temple Kaidala.JPG|thumb|Vishnu relief adorning entrance of Channakeshava Temple, Kaidala]]\n\n== Chennakeshava temple ==\n\nSubsequently, Jakanacharya received a vision to build the [[Chennakeshava temple]] in his native place Kridapura. After this was completed, legend has it that God restored his right hand. In celebration of this incident, Kridapura was henceforth called ''Kaidala''. The term ''Kai'' in [[Kannada]] means \"hand\".<ref name=sharath/> Local non-government organizations in the state of Karnataka have been trying to raise funds to protect the Chennakeshava temple at Kaidala.\n\n== The Jakanna chary Awards ==\n\nThe government of Karnataka confers the  ''[[Jakanachari Award]]s'' to talented sculptors and craftsmen from the state every year to celebrate the contributions of this legendary architect. {{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Film ==\n\nIn 1964, a Kannada biographical film about him, ''Amarashilpi Jakanachari'' starring [[Kalyan Kumar]] was produced. The veteran cinematographer BS Ranga was instrumental in the making of this movie, the first Kannada colour movie.<ref name=deccan>{{cite news|last=DHNS|title=He brought colour to Kannada cinema|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/120234/he-brought-colour-kannada-cinema.html|accessdate=21 June 2012|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=12 December 2010}}</ref> Also in 1964, a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] remake of the movie titled [[Amara Shilpi Jakkanna]] starring [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] and [[Saroja Devi]] was released to popular success.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/aug92005/spectrum92548200588.asp Article on the life of Jakanachari]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2000/01/01/stories/04012108.htm Article on Jakanachari state award]\n*[https://archive.is/20130121103109/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Content/Aug232007/state2007082320946.asp?section=updatenews Article on Jakanachari state award]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amarashilpi Jakanachari}}\n[[Category:History of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Tumkur]]\n[[Category:Kannada people]]\n[[Category:Indian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Artists from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:12th-century Indian sculptors]]\n", "name_user": "Vijender.sriramoju1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amarashilpi_Jakanachari"}
{"title_page": "Mike Zambidis", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek kickboxer}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Mike Zambidis\n| native_name     = \u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u0396\u03b1\u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2\n| native_name_lang= gr\n| image           = Mike Zambidis.png\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Mich\u00e1lis Zamb\u00eddis\n| other_names     = Iron Mike, Turkeater\n| nationality     = [[Greeks|Greek]]\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1980|7|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Porto Rafti]], [[Greece]]\n| fighting_out_of = \n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| height          = {{height|m=1.67|precision=1}}\n| weight          = {{convert|70|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class    = [[Welterweight]] <br> [[Middleweight]]\n| style           = [[Muay Thai]], [[Kickboxing]] <ref>http://www.ironmikezambidis.com/el/biography</ref>\n| stance          =\n| team            = Zambidis Club\n| trainer         = Kru Mario Barbatsas\n| years_active    = 15 (2000\u20132015)\n| kickbox_win     = 157\n| kickbox_kowin   = 87\n| kickbox_loss    = 24\n| kickbox_koloss  = 7\n| kickbox_draw    = \n| kickbox_nc      = \n| occupation      = \n| spouse          = \n| relatives       = \n| students        = \n| university      =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.ironmikezambidis.com}}\n| boxrec          =\n| sherdog         =\n| updated         = June 28, 2015\n}}\n\n'''Michalis \"Iron Mike\" Zambidis''' ([[Greek language|Greek:]] \u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u0396\u03b1\u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2; born July 15, 1980) is a professional [[Greece|Greek]] [[kickboxer]] and [[martial artist]]. He is a 17 time World Champion, including former SUPERKOMBAT Middleweight Champion. He mostly competed in the [[K-1|K-1 MAX]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hellenicathletes.com/athletes.php?athlete_id=9\n |title       = Mike's Profile\n |accessdate  = 2007-12-05\n |publisher   = www.hellenicathletes.com\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071101063903/http://www.hellenicathletes.com/athletes.php?athlete_id=9\n |archivedate = 2007-11-01\n}}</ref>\n\n==Biography and career==\nMike Zambidis started training in martial arts before he was nine years old with his brother Spiros Zambidis and his best friend Lazaros Filipas. He has trained in [[Shotokan]], [[Boxing]], [[Kickboxing]], [[Muay Thai]], [[Wrestling]], [[sanshou]] and   [[Pankration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyknux.com/forum/showthread.php?p=955025#post955025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828113049/http://www.bloodyknux.com/forum/showthread.php?p=955025#post955025|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 August 2008|title=BLOODYKNUX.COM EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW: 1 ON 1 WITH K1 MAX SUPERSTAR \"IRON\" MIKE ZAMBIDIS - BloodyKnux.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> He started competing professionally in 2000, scoring a string of victories over notable opponents. In particular he is also known by the nickname \"Turkeater\" due to the fact that he never lost to a Turkish fighter and scored eleven victories against Turkish opposition, with a final score of 11-0. So far, the majority of his wins have been knock-outs. He has been technically knocked out twice himself early in his career due to cuts, but after 2002, his next technical knock-out defeat came in 2008 against [[Andy Souwer]] in an extra round.\n\nFrom 2000 till 2002, Zambidis defeated notable kickboxer Jenk Behic twice, G\u00fcrkan \u00d6zkan twice (who outweighed Zambidis by 30 pounds), Baris Nezif, Wanlop Sosathopan, Bakari Tounkara, Matteo Sciacca and Petr Polak. In 2002, he knocked out the strong and experienced<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironlife.com/forum/showthread.php?t=86643|title=Ironlife.com|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.fightingmaster.com/legends/dekkers/best_fights/kassrioui.htm \"Fighting Master\"]</ref> [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-[[Morocco|Moroccan]] Hassan Kassrioui. On November 26, 2002 he won the K-1 Oceania MAX 2002 title after defeating [[John Wayne Parr]] in the final.\n\nIn 2003, promoter [[Tarik Solak]] arranged Zambidis' debut fight in [[Japan]] against 2002 World [[K-1|K-1 Max]] Champion [[Albert Kraus]], whom he knocked out in the 2nd round. In April 2005, Zambidis knocked out with a right hook the popular [[Norifumi Yamamoto|Norifumi \"Kid\" Yamamoto]], in front of thousands of the [[Japan]]ese kickboxer's fans. Zambidis' weakness seems to be receiving low kicks, as was seen in his 2006 defeat by Japanese [[Yoshihiro Sato]], who, despite getting hurt by Zambidis' punches, managed to land many kicks and knees which racked up enough points to \"secure a unanimous decision.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071223045553/http://www.mmaringreport.com/k-1/kids-quick-ko-headlines-heros.html Kid's Quick KO Headlines Hero's\"] Retrieved 22-Mar-2011</ref> Zambidis is a 4 time national champion in kickboxing as well as holding a large number of international titles.\n\nIn addition to his many outstanding fights, the [[K-1 World MAX 2010 -70kg World Championship Tournament Final|K-1 World MAX 2010 Final 16]] match on October the 3rd, 2010 against [[Chahid Oulad El Hadj]] was notable as being one of the most exciting of his career. In addition, as stated by ring side commentators \"Sugar\" [[Ray Sefo]] and Michael \"The Voice\" Schiavello, this contest was one by which a standard was set for other K-1 fights. However, Zambidis did not make it to the final as he lost to [[Giorgio Petrosyan]] by controversial unanimous decision. Zambidis clearly knocked down Petrosyan in the fight, but it was ruled a slip by the referee. Therefore, Petrosyan did not lose the round 10-8 as he should have, and the fight was not permitted to go to an extension fourth round. At the time, Zambidis came the closest to breaking Petrosyan's legendary undefeated streak.\n\nZambidis fought a rubber match (both having won 1 match apiece) with Australian Muay Thai champion [[John Wayne Parr]] in May 2011. He lost by TKO (three knockdowns) in round 1.\n\nHe defeated Reece McAllister by unanimous decision in the quarter-finals of the ''[[K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final]]'' in Athens, Greece on December 15, 2012. He was then battered into submission by the eventual champion [[Murthel Groenhart]] in the semis. The much larger Groenhart ruthlessly trashed Zambidis with knees and punches, forcing his corner to stop the fight at the end of round two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2000:k-1-world-max-final-8-tournament-line-up&catid=36:k-1|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2134:k-1-world-max-2012-final-live-results&catid=39:europe&Itemid=59|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was expected to compete in a four-man tournament in Russia on May 25, 2013, facing [[Dzhabar Askerov]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2345:mike-zambidis-dzhabar-askerov-artur-kyshenko-and-yuri-bessmertny-set-for-4-man-tournament-in-russia&catid=37:kickboxing|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> However, he was replaced by [[Enriko Gogokhia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fightsportasia.com/2013/05/15/mike-zambidis-out-of-legends-4-man-tournament-in-russia-replaced-by-enriko-gogohiya/ |title=Mike Zambidis Out of LEGENDS 4 Man Tournament in Russia; Replaced by Enriko Gogohiya |author=Fight Sport Asia |work=Fight Sport Asia |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024104815/http://fightsportasia.com/2013/05/15/mike-zambidis-out-of-legends-4-man-tournament-in-russia-replaced-by-enriko-gogohiya/ |archivedate=24 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nZambidis beat Harun Kina by unanimous decision for the vacant SUPERKOMBAT Middleweight Championship at SUPERKOMBAT VIP Edition in Bucharest, Romania on August 31, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2616:mike-zambidis-to-headline-superkombat-vip-edition&catid=37:kickboxing|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2635:mike-zambidis-wins-at-superkombat-vip-edition&catid=39:europe&Itemid=59|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was scheduled to fight Elam Ngor at the ''K-1 World MAX 2013 World Championship Tournament Final 16'' in Majorca, Spain on September 14, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2558:k-1-announces-k-1-world-max-final-16-in-spain&catid=36:k-1|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2640:k-1-announces-k-1-world-max-2013-final-16-tournament-fights&catid=36:k-1|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> However, he withdrew from the tournament and was replaced by Ismat Aghazade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2645:a-few-k-1-updates-zambo-out-stream-is-now-free&catid=36:k-1|title=LiverKick - LiverKick|author=Dave Walsh|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe lost to [[Xu Yan (kickboxer)|Xu Yan]] by unanimous decision, suffering knockdowns in rounds one and two, at ''Hero Legends'' in Jinan, China on January 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muaythaiauthority.com/2014/01/hero-legends-2014-results-and-recap.html |title=Hero Legends 2014 Results and Recap ~ Muay Thai Authority |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106040354/http://www.muaythaiauthority.com/2014/01/hero-legends-2014-results-and-recap.html |archivedate=6 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nZambidis and [[Batu Khasikov]] had a rematch fight and challenge the WKN Heavyweight Kickboxing World Championship at Fight Night: Battle of Moscow XV event in [[Moscow, Russia]] on March 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightmag.net/?p=27361|title=Leading show in Russia \u2018Fight Nights\u2019 sanctions with WKN|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> The Russian Batu Khasikov won the battle again for the second time.\n\nHe won his first defence of his SUPERKOMBAT middleweight title against Harun Kina on January 17 at Iron Challenge 2015 from [[Athens, Greece]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmaplus.co.uk/kickboxing/superkombat-mike-zambidis-defend-middleweight-title-harun-kina/#sthash.DB8pKAGV.wobtI9vk.dpbs|title=Superkombat: Mike Zambidis to defend middleweight title against Harun Kina|publisher=mmaplus.co.uk|date=12 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015 he announced he would retire after his final fight in June against [[Steve Moxon]], in his home country of Greece. This happened on 5 June 2015.\n\nIn October 2017, he participated in the reality game [[Nomads (reality show)|Nomads]].\n\nIn March 2019,  returned to active action after 3.5 years off abstention for 1st professional boxing match vs Venezuelan Antonio Gomez and he won with one hand Literally following an injury sustained during the round.\n\n==Titles==\n* 2019 BREAKOUT. Champion\n* 2015 World W.K.U. Champion\n* 2015 W.I.P.U. \u201cKing of the Ring\u201d Oriental Rules Super Welterweight World Champion \u221271&nbsp;kg (6th title defence)\n* 2015 SUPERKOMBAT Middleweight Championship -71&nbsp;kg/156.5lb (2nd title defence)\n* 2013 SUPERKOMBAT Middleweight Championship -71&nbsp;kg/156.5lb (One time)\n* 2012  [[2012 in K-1 Events#K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final|K-1 World MAX]] 3rd Place\n* 2012  W.I.P.U. \"King of the Ring\" Oriental Rules Super Welterweight World Champion -71&nbsp;kg (5th title defence)\n* 2011  W5 World Grand Prix KO World Champion -71&nbsp;kg<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.ironmikezambidis.com/en/articles/o_micales_zampides_katakta_ton_pagkosmio_titlo_w5\n| title=Iron Mike wins the W5 world title!!!\n| last=\n| first=\n| accessdate=2011-04-09\n| publisher=www.ironmikezambidis.com\n}}</ref>\n* 2011  W.I.P.U. \"King of the Ring\" Oriental Rules Super Welterweight World Champion -70&nbsp;kg (4th title defence)<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.ironmikezambidis.com/en/articles/triambeutes_sto_iron_challenge_o_micales_zampides\n| title=Mike Zambidis wins Iron Challenge and retains his title\n| last=\n| first=\n| accessdate=2011-03-16\n| publisher=www.ironmikezambidis.com\n}}</ref>\n* 2010  [[K-1 World MAX 2010 -70kg World Championship Tournament Final|K-1 World MAX]] 3rd Place\n* 2009  World PROFI World Champion (1st title defence)<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x89x65_mike-zambidis-vs-rhassan-muhareb_sport\n| title=Mike Zambidis vs Rhassan Muhareb\n| last=\n| first=\n| accessdate=2011-03-16\n| publisher=www.dailymotion.com\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.facebook.com/topic.php?uid=2248927671&topic=7276\n| title=Newsletter 23/1/09 - ironimkezambidis.com\n| last=\n| first=\n| accessdate=2011-03-16\n| publisher=www.facebook.com\n}}</ref>\n* 2008  W.I.P.U. \"King of the Ring\" Oriental Rules Super Welterweight World Champion -70&nbsp;kg (3rd title defence)<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.lordofrings.gr/index.php?mid=news_details&newsID=1575\n| title=Iron Challenge - Lord of Rings (In Greek)\n| last=\n| first=\n| accessdate=2011-03-16\n| publisher=www.lordofrings.gr\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721081743/http://www.lordofrings.gr/index.php?mid=news_details&newsID=1575\n| archive-date=2011-07-21\n| url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\